courses.name: Introduction to Physiologic Adaptations of Marine Mammals

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: Systems approach to physiology of marine mammals in their aquatic environment. Highlights unique features of cardiovascular, respiratory, renal, urinary, and reproductive systems. Introduces relevant physiology, and makes comparisons to human condition and disease.
cmCourseInfo.title: Introduction to Physiologic Adaptations of Marine Mammals
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: (BIO120H1, BIO130H1), CHM136H1/CHM151Y1. Students who do not have all of the required prerequisites are encouraged to contact the course coordinator to seek a waiver.

courses.name: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology I

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: Control systems, feedback, networks, and both neonatal and adult cardiovascular and respiratory control are the topics examined in detail using homeostasis as a unifying theme. Tutorials involve computer simulations, case studies and/or experimental design. This course is designed for students in the Physiology Specialist and Biological Physics Specialist Programs, although permission is granted to students in other programs upon approval by the Department.
cmCourseInfo.title: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology I
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: BCH210H1, PSL300H1, PSL301H1, MAT100-series

breadthTypes.description: BR=4 Living Things and Their Environment

courses.name: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology II

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: Molecular, cellular and organismic physiology of the central nervous system, gut, pancreas and glucose-sensing tissues; CNS diseases, obesity and diabetes are used as model systems. Tutorials involve computer simulations. This course is designed for students in the Physiology Specialist and Biological Physics Specialist Programs, although permission is granted to students in other programs upon approval by the Department.

cmCourseInfo.description: Extend molecular biology concepts to current scientific literature in mammalian physiology. Apply these principles to disease and complex behaviours. cmCourseInfo.description: Regenerative medicine promises to restore body function that has been lost due to disease, damage or age. Students will explore selected molecular, stem cell and tissue engineering developments to better understand how the body normally functions and how cells, tissues, and organs can be repaired or replaced.
cmCourseInfo.title: Regenerative Medicine
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: PSL300H1, PSL301H1

cmCourseInfo.description: This course provides an in-depth review of the development and function of the male and female reproductive systems. Topics include sex determination and differentiation, steroidogenesis, gametogenesis, hormonal control of the reproductive axis, the female ovulatory cycle, fertilization and implantation, infertility and assisted reproduction approaches. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL420H1/LMP2100H
cmCourseInfo.title: Reproduction: Development and Function
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: A minimum grade of 78% is required in PSL300H1 and PSL301H1. If minimum grade has not been met students are advised to contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

courses.name: Pregnancy and Birth: From Implantation to Newborn Life

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: General overview of the integrated physiological events associated with fetal development, pregnancy and birth. The approach emphasizes physiological processes using insights gained from studies of humans, animals, cells and genes. Where appropriate the clinical consequences of aberrant development are reviewed. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL421H1/PSL1421H
cmCourseInfo.title: Pregnancy and Birth: From Implantation to Newborn Life
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: A final grade of 75% or higher in each of PSL300H1 and PSL301H1. If minimum is not reached, please contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

courses.name: Mechanisms of Neural and Endocrinal Secretion

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: Exocytosis and other aspects of secretion mainly in neurons and neuroendocrine cells, but also in pancreatic cells. Topics include synapse anatomy and physiology, synaptic plasma membrane and vesicle proteins, membrane fusion, genetic tools, endocrine secretion, plasticity in neurotransmitter release, diseases arising from secretion defects.
cmCourseInfo.title: Mechanisms of Neural and Endocrinal Secretion
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: BCH210H1, PSL300H1/(BIO240H1, BIO241H1), PSL350H1/CSB349H1/BCH311H1/MGY311Y1

cmCourseInfo.description: This course covers the physiology underlying sleep and circadian rhythms, and their impact on important physiological processes and health. The integrative nature of the basic physiological processes is emphasized via discussions and clinical presentations. Overall, the aim is to present the full spectrum of integrative physiology from molecules and cells to understanding the sick patient.

cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText:
PSL300H1, PSL301H1

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

Students need to acquired a supervisor under the Department of Physiology and must submit a completed PSL498Y1Y ballot by Friday, August 26, before being enrolled. Ballots are available on the course website: http://www.physiology.utoronto.ca/psl498y-project-physiology. 

For more information please contact the undergraduate assistant at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.

Delivery Instructions

An independent research project course with remote or in-person projects under faculty supervision. The location of the research depends on the supervisor and project chosen. Students are required to find a supervisor within the Department of Physiology.
